224
00:17:12,490 --> 00:17:14,280
Well, it's ridiculous.

225
00:17:14,360 --> 00:17:16,910
Who am I to make a criticism to someone like you?

226
00:17:16,990 --> 00:17:19,320
It's all right, I can take it.

227
00:17:22,200 --> 00:17:24,000
Well, it's brilliantly written.

228
00:17:24,080 --> 00:17:26,670
But then everything you write is brilliant.

229
00:17:26,750 --> 00:17:28,710
Pretty rough so far?

230
00:17:30,460 --> 00:17:32,380
The swearing, Paul.

231
00:17:34,470 --> 00:17:36,300
There, I said it.

232
00:17:37,180 --> 00:17:39,930
The... The profanity bothers you?

233
00:17:40,140 --> 00:17:42,430
It has no nobility.

234
00:17:42,520 --> 00:17:46,940
These are slum kids.I was a slum kid.

235
00:17:47,020 --> 00:17:48,440
Everybody talks like that.

236
00:17:48,520 --> 00:17:50,690
They do not!

237
00:17:50,770 --> 00:17:53,070
What do you think I say when I go to the feed store in town?

238
00:17:53,150 --> 00:17:56,700
"Now, Wally, give me a bag of that F-ing pig feed

239
00:17:56,780 --> 00:17:59,490
"and 10 pounds of that bitchly cow corn"?

240
00:17:59,570 --> 00:18:02,490
And in the bank, do I tell Mrs. Bollinger,

241
00:18:02,490 --> 00:18:04,330
"Here's one big bastard of a check,

242
00:18:04,410 --> 00:18:06,410
"give me some of your Christing money"?

243
00:18:06,500 --> 00:18:10,510
There! Look there! See what you made me do?

244
00:18:14,800 --> 00:18:17,300
Paul, I'm sorry.

245
00:18:17,380 --> 00:18:19,010
I'm so sorry.

246
00:18:24,310 --> 00:18:29,730
Sometimes I get so worked up. Can you ever forgive me?

247
00:18:30,350 --> 00:18:32,230
It's fine.

248
00:18:38,200 --> 00:18:40,200
I love you, Paul.

249
00:18:43,870 --> 00:18:48,780
Your mind. Your creativity. That's all I meant.

250
00:19:28,700 --> 00:19:30,660
Well, this sure is fun.

251
00:19:41,680 --> 00:19:44,260
Virginia, when you're in this car

252
00:19:44,350 --> 00:19:46,180
you're not my wife, you're my deputy.

253
00:19:48,270 --> 00:19:49,720
Well, this deputy'd rather be home

254
00:19:49,810 --> 00:19:52,560
under the covers with the sheriff.

255
00:19:53,860 --> 00:19:56,440
- Stop. Stop  - What? What?

256
00:20:07,540 --> 00:20:10,370
See that broken limb?

257
00:20:10,450 --> 00:20:12,120
Could've been the weight of the snow.

258
00:20:12,210 --> 00:20:15,540
Yeah? Could've been a rotten branch, could've been the wind,

259
00:20:15,630 --> 00:20:17,920
could've been a lot of things.

260
00:20:47,280 --> 00:20:48,370
[GRUNTS]

261
00:20:50,620 --> 00:20:51,660
Damn!

